(70, 27, 0, 'abcl', '<p><span style="color: #3f3f3f; font-family: georgia; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;">True, social media and technology was used in the 2009 Lok Sabha polls, too. But in the last two years, there has been a marked increase in uptake of digital tools by political figures and parties. It started with various "official" Twitter handles and Facebook pages trickling in and reached a crescendo with the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><a style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; font-size: 15px; background-color: #ffffff; color: #024d99; text-decoration: none; font-family: georgia; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;" href="http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/%22#Feku%22-vs-%22#Pappu%22-mudslinging-on-Twitter">"#Feku" vs "#Pappu" mudslinging on Twitter</a><span style="color: #3f3f3f; font-family: georgia; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;">.<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><br style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: #3f3f3f; font-family: georgia; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;" /><br style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: #3f3f3f; font-family: georgia; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;" /><span style="color: #3f3f3f; font-family: georgia; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;">Then there has been a spate of Google Hangouts, which saw policymakers and politicians reach out to the electorate via videoconference. In April, a study by the IRIS Knowledge Foundation and the Internet and Mobile Association of India (IMAI) even said that social media is likely to impact 160 Lok Sabha seats. With a captive audience, it''s now time to take cybercampaigning to the next level.<span class="Apple-converted-space"> <br /></span></span></p>', '', 0, 0, 0, '', 'inoerp', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'inoerp', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
